{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "ParticleCollectionEfficiency",
        "description": "Slinn (1983) semi-empirical collision (collection) efficiency E between a falling raindrop and an aerosol particle, the kernel of below-cloud particle scavenging (Eqs. 20.53-20.54, Seinfeld & Pandis, 2006). E is the sum of three collection mechanisms — Brownian diffusion (E_diff, important for sub-0.1 µm particles), interception (E_int), and inertial impaction (E_imp, important for super-µm particles, switched on only when the Stokes number exceeds the critical Stokes number S* of Eq. 20.54) — and is clamped to a maximum of 1. The competition between the diffusion and impaction mechanisms produces the Greenfield gap: a collection-efficiency minimum at accumulation-mode (~0.1-1 µm) particle sizes. Migrated from AtmosphericDeposition.jl@e4468c79 src/seinfeld_pandis_2006_ch20.jl:365 (`ParticleCollectionEfficiency` @component). The upstream component carries the single equation E ~ slinn_collection_efficiency(D_p, U_t, d_p, ρ_p, T); the helper function and its sub-helpers (particle_diffusivity, particle_relaxation_time, particle_terminal_velocity) are decomposed here into 18 named intermediate algebraic states (Re, D_diff, Sc, τ, St, S_star, E_diff, E_int, E_imp, ...) mirroring the helper's local variables, so each equation maps to one source line. Observed-only: all 18 equations are algebraic — the five raindrop/aerosol/thermodynamic inputs and six physical constants are parameters, and Re through E are the algebraic outputs.",
        "tags": [
            "atmospheric_deposition",
            "seinfeld-pandis",
            "wet-scavenging",
            "below-cloud-scavenging",
            "ch20",
            "observed-only"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "AtmosphericDeposition.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-dbc5)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., & Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd ed., Chapter 20: Wet Deposition, pp. 932-979. John Wiley & Sons, Inc. Eqs. 20.53-20.54 define the Slinn (1983) particle-drop collection efficiency. ISBN 978-0-471-72018-8."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Slinn, W. G. N. (1983). Precipitation scavenging. In Atmospheric Sciences and Power Production (D. Randerson, ed.), Ch. 11, pp. 466-532. U.S. Department of Energy, DOE/TIC-27601. Original source of the semi-empirical collision-efficiency parameterization adopted as Eqs. 20.53-20.54 by Seinfeld & Pandis (2006)."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "ParticleCollectionEfficiency": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: AtmosphericDeposition.jl@e4468c79c8dd4aae88646cd16d6bcf290874742c:src/seinfeld_pandis_2006_ch20.jl:365\nUpstream `ParticleCollectionEfficiency` is an MTK `@component` with D_p, U_t, d_p, ρ_p, T as input `@parameters` and a single output `@variable` E(t), related by one equation E ~ slinn_collection_efficiency(D_p, U_t, d_p, ρ_p, T) — the Slinn (1983) semi-empirical raindrop-aerosol collision (collection) efficiency, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Eqs. 20.53-20.54. It returns `System(eqs, t, vars, params; name)` with no subsystems, so it is a flat algebraic model.\n\nDecomposition: the upstream `slinn_collection_efficiency` is a module-level helper function whose result is one large symbolic expression. Inlining it verbatim into a single equation AST would duplicate the Re / Sc / St / S_star / stokes_diff / safe_ratio subexpressions many times over (Re alone is referenced ~6 times, stokes_diff ~5), producing a several-hundred-node tree that is not reviewable. Instead the helper's named local variables are migrated as 18 intermediate algebraic states — one equation each, in the helper's own evaluation order — so every .esm equation maps to exactly one source line and the migration is line-checkable. This is mathematically identical to the single upstream equation (the intermediates are common-subexpression names); after `mtkcompile` all 18 reduce to observed quantities and E is the same function of the five inputs as upstream. The three module-level sub-helpers `particle_diffusivity` (Stokes-Einstein, src line 290), `particle_relaxation_time` (src line 268) and `particle_terminal_velocity` (src line 278) are inlined into the D_diff, τ and u_t_particle equations respectively. This extends the sibling air_refreshing.esm / cloud_ice_uptake.esm convention of inlining upstream helper functions, with named intermediates because this component's single helper is far larger than those siblings'.\n\nThe six module-level `@constants` (μ_air_sp, ρ_air_sp, μ_w_sp, ρ_w_sp, g_sp, kB_sp) migrate as fixed-default `type: parameter` entries holding their upstream numeric values (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006; μ_air from Table A.7), per the rig convention for translating MTK `@constants` (matches cloud_ice_uptake.esm). The upstream `cbrt(Sc)` cube root in the Brownian term is re-expressed as Sc^(1/3) with the `^` op, since the spec §4.2 elementary-function set has no `cbrt`; Sc (a Schmidt number) is always strictly positive so the two are numerically equivalent. Julia's `pi` is inlined as the float64 literal 3.141592653589793. The upstream `1//12` and `2//3` exact rationals are kept as integer-literal `/` nodes. The component has no `ifelse` nodes: the upstream final clamp ifelse(E_total > 1, 1, E_total) is migrated as min(1, E_total) — the identical upper clamp and the spec §4.2-preferred AST encoding of a limiter — and the upstream impaction term ifelse(stokes_diff ≤ 0, zero(safe_ratio), safe_ratio*sqrt(safe_ratio)) is migrated as safe_ratio*sqrt(safe_ratio) directly, because safe_ratio = max(0, stokes_diff)/(max(0, stokes_diff) + 2/3) is already exactly 0 whenever stokes_diff ≤ 0 (the max(0, ·) numerator), so both ifelse branches are bit-identical and the conditional is provably dead code. Eliding it is numerically exact and keeps the model free of `Piecewise`: a `Max` reachable from a `Piecewise` condition trips a sympy lambdify-printer path (`simplify_logic` substitutes every free symbol with 0, and the resulting 0/0 in the zeroed Reynolds/Stokes expressions reaches `Max` as a NaN). The max(0, ·) in safe_ratio is retained — it keeps the sqrt argument non-negative, the upstream author's own stated reason for the max ('avoid negative base in power'). `system_kind` is left unset (zero differential states — no D operator), consistent with the observed-only siblings air_refreshing.esm / atmospheric_thermo.esm / total_molar_conc.esm.\n\nThe five input parameters carry their upstream `@parameter` defaults (D_p = 1e-3 m, U_t = 4 m/s, d_p = 1e-6 m, ρ_p = 1000 kg/m^3, T = 298 K). Upstream provides three relevant test items: `Slinn Collection Efficiency (Eq. 20.53)` exercises the helper at small / medium / large aerosol diameters with inequality assertions (E_small > 1e-4, E_small > E_medium, all E ≤ 1); `Critical Stokes Number (Eq. 20.54)` checks the S* formula; and the helper-function items pin particle_relaxation_time ≈ 3.23e-6 s, particle_terminal_velocity ≈ 3.17e-5 m/s and particle_diffusivity ≈ 2.54e-11 m^2/s at d_p = 1e-6 m, ρ_p = 1000 kg/m^3, T = 298 K. The inline tests here pin exact values: default_parameters uses the component defaults (which coincide with the upstream helper-test inputs) and asserts τ, u_t_particle and D_diff against those upstream reference values plus the full chain; aitken_mode_aerosol / accumulation_mode_aerosol / coarse_mode_aerosol reproduce the upstream `Slinn Collection Efficiency` small / medium / large cases (D_p = 2e-3 m, U_t = 6.5 m/s, d_p ∈ {1e-8, 1e-6, 1e-5} m) and confirm E_small > E_medium and the Greenfield-gap minimum at accumulation-mode size; coarse_mode_aerosol and dense_coarse_aerosol exercise the St > S* inertial-impaction branch and the sqrt(ρ_w/ρ_p) density correction; cold_temperature exercises the temperature dependence of the Brownian term; efficiency_clamp drives E_total > 1 so the Eq. 20.53 maximum-of-1 clamp fires (E pinned to 1.0).\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-6, abs=1e-12): observed-only algebraic system (no ODE integration). The 18 equations form a triangular chain of +, -, *, /, ^, sqrt, log, max and min on float64; round-off is ~1e-16 per op, so rel=1e-6 leaves ample headroom across the tested ranges (Re ~ 1e2, Sc ~ 5e3 to 3e7, E ~ 1e-4 to 1). abs=1e-12 gates the exact-zero intermediates (safe_ratio, E_imp_unscaled, E_imp) in the no-impaction cases, where a pure relative tolerance would be degenerate."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-06,
                "abs": 1e-12
            },
            "variables": {
                "D_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.001,
                    "description": "Raindrop diameter"
                },
                "U_t": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 4.0,
                    "description": "Terminal velocity of the raindrop"
                },
                "d_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1e-06,
                    "description": "Aerosol particle diameter"
                },
                "ρ_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "default": 1000.0,
                    "description": "Aerosol particle density"
                },
                "T": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "K",
                    "default": 298.0,
                    "description": "Temperature"
                },
                "μ_air_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/(m*s)",
                    "default": 1.72e-05,
                    "description": "Dynamic viscosity of air (Table A.7, Seinfeld & Pandis 2006)"
                },
                "ρ_air_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "default": 1.225,
                    "description": "Air density at standard conditions (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006)"
                },
                "μ_w_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/(m*s)",
                    "default": 0.001,
                    "description": "Dynamic viscosity of water"
                },
                "ρ_w_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg/m^3",
                    "default": 1000.0,
                    "description": "Water density"
                },
                "g_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s^2",
                    "default": 9.81,
                    "description": "Gravitational acceleration"
                },
                "kB_sp": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "kg*m^2/(s^2*K)",
                    "default": 1.3806488e-23,
                    "description": "Boltzmann constant"
                },
                "Re": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Raindrop Reynolds number based on drop radius, Re = D_p*U_t*ρ_air/(2*μ_air) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "D_diff": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^2/s",
                    "description": "Brownian diffusivity of the aerosol particle (Stokes-Einstein relation)"
                },
                "Sc": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Particle Schmidt number, Sc = μ_air/(ρ_air*D_diff) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "τ": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "s",
                    "description": "Particle relaxation time in the Stokes drag regime, τ = ρ_p*d_p^2/(18*μ_air)"
                },
                "u_t_particle": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "description": "Particle Stokes settling (terminal) velocity, u_t = τ*g"
                },
                "St": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Stokes number of the aerosol particle relative to the raindrop, St = 2*τ*(U_t - u_t)/D_p (dimensionless)"
                },
                "φ": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Aerosol-to-raindrop diameter ratio, φ = d_p/D_p (dimensionless)"
                },
                "ω": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Water-to-air dynamic viscosity ratio, ω = μ_w/μ_air (dimensionless)"
                },
                "S_star": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Critical Stokes number (Eq. 20.54) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E_diff": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Brownian diffusion term of the collection efficiency (Eq. 20.53, first line) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E_int": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Interception term of the collection efficiency (Eq. 20.53, second line) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "stokes_diff": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Stokes-number excess over the critical Stokes number, St - S* (dimensionless)"
                },
                "safe_ratio": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Clamped impaction ratio max(0, St-S*)/(max(0, St-S*) + 2/3) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "density_scaling": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Particle-density correction factor sqrt(ρ_w/ρ_p) for the impaction term (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E_imp_unscaled": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Inertial impaction term before the density correction; zero when St ≤ S* (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E_imp": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Inertial impaction term of the collection efficiency (Eq. 20.53, third line) (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E_total": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Sum of the three collection-efficiency terms before clamping (dimensionless)"
                },
                "E": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Collection efficiency between a raindrop and an aerosol particle (Eq. 20.53), clamped to a maximum of 1 (dimensionless)"
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "_comment": "Reynolds number based on drop radius (slinn_collection_efficiency, src line 310): Re = D_p*U_t*ρ_air/(2*μ_air)",
                    "lhs": "Re",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    "D_p",
                                    "U_t",
                                    "ρ_air_sp"
                                ]
                            },
